  "prompt": "Who was Adam Smith and why was he so important?",
  "response": "Adam Smith (1723-1790) was a Scottish economist, philosopher, and author who is widely considered the father of modern economics. He is best known for his influential book \"The Wealth of Nations,\" published in 1776, which laid the foundation for classical economic theory.\n\nKey contributions and importance:\n\n1. Free Market Economics\n- Introduced the concept of the \"invisible hand\" - the idea that individuals pursuing their own self-interest can benefit society as a whole\n- Argued for minimal government intervention in economic affairs\n- Advocated for free trade and limited economic regulations\n\n2. Division of Labor\n- Explained how specialization and breaking down production into specific tasks could dramatically increase economic productivity\n- Used the example of a pin factory to demonstrate how workers performing specific roles could produce far more pins collectively than working individually\n\n3. Economic Theory\n- Developed foundational theories about value, price, and market dynamics\n- Explained how supply and demand interact to determine prices\n- Explored the relationship between labor, production, and wealth creation\n\n4. Moral Philosophy\n- Wrote \"The Theory of Moral Sentiments,\" which explored human ethics and social behavior\n- Argued that human beings have natural sympathy and capacity for moral judgment\n\nSmith's work profoundly influenced economic thinking and helped establish economics as a formal academic discipline. His ideas fundamentally shaped modern capitalism and continue to be studied and debated today.",
